[[File:3313-13-live-at-the-apollo.jpg|thumb|Cover of the ''Live at the Apollo'' book.]]
'''{{frac|33|1|3}}''' (Thirty-Three and a Third) is a series of books with each volume written about a single album.<ref name=PMBarker>{{cite web |url=https://www.popmatters.com/yoder-060403-2496049204.html |title=Introduction and Interview with Series Editor David Barker |work=PopMatters |last=Yoder |first=Anne K. |date=April 2, 2006 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522045143/https://www.popmatters.com/yoder-060403-2496049204.html |archivedate=2018-05-22 }}</ref> The series title refers to the speed of a [[vinyl LP]].<ref name=LATimes>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-thirty-three-books-20140831-story.html |title=33⅓ book series celebrates records – and its 10th anniversary |work=Los Angeles Times |last=Benfer |first=Amy |date=August 28, 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406131230/http://www.latimes.com/books/jacketcopy/la-ca-jc-thirty-three-books-20140831-story.html |archivedate=April 6, 2018 }}</ref>

== History ==
Originally published by [[Continuum International Publishing Group|Continuum]],<ref name=BillboardBrown>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6480462/33-1-3-series-survival-harry-potter |title=How the 33 1/3 Series, In Spite of Two Shrinking Industries, Continues to Thrive |work=Billboard |last=Brown |first=Harley |date=February 25, 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170726161236/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6480462/33-1-3-series-survival-harry-potter |archivedate=July 26, 2017 |access-date=May 5, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> the series was founded by editor David Barker in 2003.<ref name=PMBarker/> At the time, Continuum published books on philosophers; series editor Ally-Jane Grossan mentioned that Barker was "an obsessive music fan who thought, 'This is a really cool idea, why don't we apply this to albums'."<ref name=BillboardBrown/> ''[[PopMatters]]'' wrote that the range consists of "obscure classics to more usual suspects by the Beach Boys, the Beatles, and the Rolling Stones".<ref name=PMBarker/>

In 2010, Continuum was bought out by [[Bloomsbury Publishing]], which continues to publish the series.<ref name=BillboardBrown/> Following a leave, Barker was replaced by Grossan in January 2013.<ref name=LATimes/> In 2016, Daphne Brooks, Kevin Dettmarr, Amanda Petrusich, and Gayle Wald assumed co-editorial duties.

Two independent books have been spun off of the series. The first, Carl Wilson's 2007 entry on [[Celine Dion]]'s ''[[Let's Talk About Love]]'', was expanded for a 2014 Bloomsbury reissue with material not specifically pertaining to the Dion album and retitled ''Let's Talk About Love: Why Other People Have Such Bad Taste''. A rejected proposal from writer [[Brett Milano]] for an entry on [[Game Theory (band)|Game Theory]]'s 1987 album ''[[Lolita Nation]]'' was instead expanded by Milano into a biography on the band's leader [[Scott Miller (pop musician)|Scott Miller]]; that project, titled ''[[Don't All Thank Me at Once|Don't All Thank Me at Once: The Lost Genius of Scott Miller]]'' was released by 125 Books in 2015.<ref name=salon-z>{{cite journal |first=Annie |last=Zaleski |title=The lost pop genius of Scott Miller |date=January 1, 2016 |journal=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |url=http://www.salon.com/2016/01/02/the_lost_pop_genius_of_scott_miller_whatever_makes_you_fall_in_love_with_a_pop_song_he_did_that/#comments |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106203544/http://www.salon.com/2016/01/02/the_lost_pop_genius_of_scott_miller_whatever_makes_you_fall_in_love_with_a_pop_song_he_did_that/#comments |archivedate=2016-01-06 }}</ref>

In August 2017, Bloomsbury announced the launch of {{frac|33|1|3}} Global,<ref name="33-1/3 Global Launch">{{cite web |url=http://333sound.com/new-series-announcement-33-13-global/ |title=New series announcement: 33 1/3 Global |work=333Sound |date=August 9, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180320215054/http://333sound.com/new-series-announcement-33-13-global/ |archivedate=2018-03-20 }}</ref> an extension of the {{frac|33|1|3}} series to popular music from around the world. The first two sub-series launched were {{frac|33|1|3}} Brazil, edited by Jason Stanyek, and {{frac|33|1|3}} Japan, edited by Noriko Manabe.<ref name="33-1/3 Japan editor">{{cite web |url=https://333sound.com/2017/08/31/33-13-global-editor-highlight-noriko-manabe/ |title=33 1/3 Global editor highlight: Noriko Manabe |work=333Sound |date=August 31, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522044201/https://333sound.com/33-13-global-editor-highlight-noriko-manabe/ |archivedate=2018-05-22 }}</ref> The first book for {{frac|33|1|3}} Brazil was ''Caetano Veloso's A Foreign Sound'' by Barbara Browning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloomsbury.com/us/series/33-13-brazil/ |title=33 1/3 Brazil |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522044307/https://bloomsbury.com/us/series/33-13-brazil/ |archivedate=2018-05-22 }}</ref> The first books for {{frac|33|1|3}} Japan were ''Supercell ft. Hatsune Miku'' by Keisuke Yamada and ''Yoko Kanno's Cowboy Bebop Soundtrack'' by Rose Bridges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bloomsbury.com/us/series/33-13-japan/ |title=33 1/3 Japan |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522044309/https://bloomsbury.com/us/series/33-13-japan/ |archivedate=2018-05-22 }}</ref>

