[[File:André Gayot.jpg|alt=André Gayot|thumb|André Gayot]] '''André Gayot''' is a French journalist. Concurrent with his studies, he started his career in 1949 at the [[ORTF]] (National French Radio) producing a show for a young audience. In 1957, he was a political columnist for the daily newspaper ''La Liberté du Massif Central'', and an editor for ''[[Paris-Presse]]''. In 1958, he joined the weekly magazine ''[[Jours de France]]''. He was appointed in 1960 director of information of the [[Republic of Niger]] where he created the information services and the daily ''Le Temps du Niger''. In 1962, he founded and directed for five years the daily ''Le Courrier de Madagascar'' in Antananarivo. He created in 1967 in Martinique the weekly ''France Antilles Spécial Dimanche''. He was in 1968 in Dakar, Senegal, leading the creation of the daily ''Le Soleil'' and of ''Les Nouvelles Imprimeries du Sénégal'', both of which paved the way to the plurality and opening of information in French West Africa. Gayot has been active in Canada where he renewed and relaunched the world's oldest French language daily, ''L'Evangéline''. He brought his expertise to the local press in Vietnam, Egypt, Mauretania, Zaïre (now Republic of Congo), Burundi and Iran.<ref>''La Gazette de la Presse francophone'' (Paris) Juillet 2005 NJ 122</ref>
In 1969, with his friends [[Henri Gault]] and [[Christian Millau]], he founded the monthly magazine ''Le Nouveau Guide'', which went against culinary traditions of the time by promoting artistically prepared food, new cooking techniques and fresh ingredients.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uIqyMMogRsMC&pg=PA85&lpg=PA85|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|year=2007|title=The 1980s|author=Bob Batchelor, Scott Stoddart}}</ref> The three also founded the ''[[Gault Millau]]'' guide,<ref>{{cite news|title=Food & Drink: Do not pass Gault before booking a table: Who judges the judges? Emily Green, as she assesses a new French guide to London's best restaurants|author=Emily Green|date=June 25, 1994|publisher=''The Independent''|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/food-and-drink/food--drink-do-not-pass-gault-before-booking-a-table-who-judges-the-judges-emily-green-as-she-assesses-a-new-french-guide-to-londons-best-restaurants-1425025.html}}</ref> and coined and promoted the term ''[[nouvelle cuisine]]''.<ref name="MILLAU2010">{{cite book|author=Christian MILLAU|title=Dictionnaire amoureux de la gastronomie|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=y9bOMlEfvr4C|page=206}}|date=16 December 2010|publisher=EDI8 - PLON|isbn=978-2-259-21171-0}}</ref> In the 1980s and 1990s, Gayot began publishing in the USA a series of restaurant guidebooks known alternatively under the Gault-Millau name or as ''Gayot Guides''. The guidebooks rated and highlighted restaurants deemed to be among the top in their region, with reviews discussing décor, service, ambience and wine lists, with an emphasis on French cuisine.<ref>{{cite news |first=Josh|last=Ozersky |title=An Alternative to the Sucky Michelin Guide |url=http://nymag.com/daily/food/2006/11/an_alternative_to_the_sucky_michelin_guide.html |publisher=[[New York Magazine]] |date=2006-11-29 |accessdate=2008-09-29 }}</ref><ref name="grubstreet 2006">{{cite web |url=http://newyork.grubstreet.com/2006/11/michelin.html |title=The Case Against the Michelin Guide |publisher=[[nymag.com]] |date=2006-11-29 |accessdate=2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120327083144/http://newyork.grubstreet.com/2006/11/michelin.html |archivedate=2012-03-27 }}</ref> After 2000, his guides were published exclusively under the name Gayot, following a disagreement with the new owners of the French Gault-Millau guides.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://zemmrate.com/22-gault-et-millau.html|title = Culinary Guide Gault et Millau|publisher = zemrate.com}}</ref>
In 1983, Gayot founded, in Paris, the monthly magazine ''Prévention Santé'' in conjunction with [[Rodale Publishing]] (Emmaus, PA USA). With son Alain and daughter Sophie, he launched in Los Angeles the website www.gayot.com devoted to gastronomy, tourism and lifestyle.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
On May 7, 1979, [[Léopold Sédar Senghor]], President of the Republic of Senegal presented Gayot, in his name and that of the President of the French Republic [[Valéry Giscard d'Estaing]] in the presence of [[Michel Debré]] former French prime minister, with the distinction of Chevalier de la Légion d'Honneur, for his humanitarian and cultural actions for Africa.<ref>''Le Nouveau Guide GaultMillau'', June 1979</ref>{{better source|date=January 2016}}
''"For exceptional services rendered to the freedom of press and promotion of the friendship between nations"'' was said on April 27, 2005, by the Ambassador of France in Washington, D.C., [[Jean-David Levitte]] as he bestowed on Gayot the award of the rank of [[Officer of the Legion of Honor]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.legiondhonneur.fr/ |title=La Légion d’Honneur |access-date=2018-10-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110225044652/http://legiondhonneur.fr/ |archive-date=2011-02-25 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> – the highest French distinction. Gayot is also an officer in the national order of Senegal (order of the Lion), in the national order of the République du Niger and in the order of the Comoros. He holds a master's degree in law and a doctorate degree in economics.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
