[[File:Bernard Sergent - Rencontres de l’imaginaire de Brocéliande 2014.JPG|thumb|Bernard Sergent in 2014]]
'''Bernard Sergent''' ({{IPA-fr|sɛʁʒɑ̃|lang}}; born 23 February 1946) is a French [[ancient history|ancient historian]] and [[comparative mythologist]]. He is researcher of the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]] and president of the Société de mythologie française.<ref>[http://www.mythofrancaise.asso.fr/index2.html "Le Conseil d'Administration comprend actuellement", ''Société de mythologie française'']</ref><ref>http://www.arbre-celtique.com/encyclopedie/sergent-bernard-2081.htm</ref>
== Publications == He has written a seminal work on [[Greek mythology]] entitled ''Homosexuality in Greek Myth'', translated into English two years later by [[Beacon Press]]. In 1986, he followed up with a study covering early [[homosexuality]] in [[Europe]], under the title of ''L'homosexualité initiatique dans l'Europe ancienne'' (Payot 1986), which has yet to be translated into English. The two studies have been published together, with a postface, as ''Homosexualité et initiation chez les peuples indo-européens''.
In ''Genèse de L'Inde'', he attacks the recent [[Indo-Aryan migration|anti-invasionist]] reconstructions of early [[India]]n history. Instead he defends the traditional hypothesis that the [[Indo-Aryans]] invaded India in the 2nd millennium BC. According to Sergent, the [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian]] populations are not autochthonous either, but of [[Africa]]n origin.<ref>http://koenraadelst.bharatvani.org/reviews/sergent.html</ref>
The book ''Les Indo-Européens - Histoire, langues, mythes'' is a general introduction to the Indo-European language family. Sergent associates the [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European language family]] with certain archaeological cultures in Southern [[Russia]], and he reconstructs an Indo-European religion (relying on the method of [[Georges Dumézil]]). He writes that the lithic assemblage of the first [[Kurgan culture]] in [[Ukraine]] (Sredni Stog II), originated from the [[Volga Delta|Volga]] and [[Ural region|South Urals]], recalls that of the [[Mesolithic]]-[[Neolithic]] sites to the east of the [[Caspian sea]], [[Dam Dam Chesme II]] and the [[Cave of Dzhebel|cave of Djebel]].<ref>See [http://encyclopedia2.thefreedictionary.com/Dzhebel Dzhebel], and V. A. Ranov and R. S. Davis (1979), ''[http://repository.brynmawr.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1006&context=anth_pubs Toward a New Outline of the Soviet Central Asian Paleolithic]''</ref> Thus, he places the roots of the Gimbutas' Kurgan cradle of Indo-Europeans in a more southern cradle, and adds that the Djebel material is related to a [[Paleolithic]] material of [[Northwestern Iran]], the [[Zarzian culture]], dated 10,000-8,500 BC, and in the more ancient [[Kebarian]] of the [[Near East]]. He concludes that more than 10,000 years ago the [[Proto-Indo-Europeans|Indo-Europeans]] were a small people grammatically, phonetically and lexically close to [[Semitic people|Semitic]]-[[Hamitic]] populations of the Near East.
In the monograph, ''Les trois fonctions indo-européennes en Grèce ancienne'', vol. 1: ''De Mycènes aux Tragique'', Sergent examines the employment of the [[Trifunctional hypothesis|Dumézilian tripartite system]] in Greek [[Epic poetry|epic]], [[Lyric poetry|lyric]] and [[Verse drama and dramatic verse|dramatic]] poetry. In a second volume, which has not been published yet, he will continue this examination with Greek [[philosophy]] and [[religion]].
His recent work, ''Celtes et Grecs'', is dedicated to comparative [[Greek mythology|Greek]] and [[Celtic mythology]]. In volume 1, ''Le livre de héros'' (Payot 1999 {{ISBN|2-228-89257-2}}), the Irish hero [[Cuchulainn]] is compared with the Greek heroes [[Achilleus]], [[Bellerophon]] and [[Melanthius]] and the Irish epic [[Táin Bó Cúailnge]] with the Greek [[Iliad]], which, according to Sergent, presuppose an Indo-European "pre-Iliad". In volume 2, ''Le livre des dieux'', Sergent argues that the Celtic and Greek [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheons]] derive from a common Indo-European inheritance.
==Works== * ''L'homosexualité initiatique dans l'Europe ancienne'', Payot 1986 {{ISBN|2-228-89052-9}} * ''Les Indo-Européens'' Payot, 1995 {{ISBN|2-228-88956-3}} * ''Genèse de l'Inde'' (Genesis of India), Payot, Paris 1997 {{ISBN|978-2-228-89116-5}} * ''De Mycènes aux Tragique'', Économica 1998 {{ISBN|2-7178-3587-3}} * ''Celtes et Grecs'', Payot, 1999 * ''La guerre à la culture: aspects des attaques contre l'intelligence dans la période jospino-raffininesque'', L'Harmattan, 2005, {{ISBN|978-2-7475-7823-3}}
===Books with English translations=== * ''Homosexuality in Greek Myth,'' tr. Arthur Goldhammer, pref. [[Georges Dumezil]]. Beacon Press, Boston, 1986. {{ISBN|0-8070-5700-2}} * {{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dfbqWF1TCyYC&pg=PA147&lpg=PA147&dq=Bernard+Sergent#v=onepage&q=Bernard%20Sergent&f=false| chapter=Paedestary and Political Life in Archaic Greek Cities| title=Gay studies from the French cultures: voices from France, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, and the Netherlands| editors=Rommel Mendès-Leite, Pierre-Olivier de Busscher| publisher=Routledge| year= 1993| isbn= 978-1-56024-436-3 }}
