[[File:Les Parques.jpg|thumb|''Les Parques'' ("The Parcæ"), [[Alfred Agache (painter)|Alfred Agache]], c 1885]]
[[File:Peter Paul Rubens - Sketches - WGA20439.jpg|thumb|left|300px|''The Triumph of Truth (The Three Parcae Spinning the Fate of [[Marie de Medici]])'' (1622-1625), by [[Peter Paul Rubens]] (1577-1640)]]
'''Nona''' was one of the [[Parcae]], the three personifications of destiny in [[Roman mythology]] (the [[Moirai]] in Greek mythology and in Germanic mythology, the [[Norns]]), and the Roman goddess of pregnancy. The Roman equivalent of the Greek [[Clotho]], she spun the thread of life from her [[distaff]] onto her [[Spindle (textiles)|spindle]]. Nona, whose name means "ninth", was called upon by pregnant women in their ninth month when the child was due to be born.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |title= The Attic Nights of Aulus Gellius; Translated into English by the Rev. W. Beloe, F.S.R., Translator of Herodotus  |page= 220 |url=https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_j3kBAAAAMAAJ#page/n321/mode/2up  |publisher= Printed for J.Johnson, St. Paul Church-Yard |year= 1795|volume = I |place= London |accessdate= 9 January 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |chapter= Tertullian, A Treatise On the Soul |title=The Ante-Nicene Fathers; Translations of the Fathers Down to A.D., The Rev. Alexander Roberts, D.D., James Donaldson, LL.D. Editors   |page= 217  |url= https://archive.org/stream/antenicenefather00robe#page/216/mode/2up |publisher= WM EERDMANS Publishing Company  |year= 1986 |volume = III |place= Grand Rapids, Michigan  |accessdate= 11 January 2018|via= Internet Archive}}</ref>

She, [[Decima (mythology)|Decima]] and [[Morta (deity)|Morta]] together controlled the metaphorical thread of life.

[[File:Les trois Parques-Marco-Bigio.jpg|thumb|''The Three Parcae'' (1540-1550), by Marco Bigio, in Villa Barberini, Rome]]
