{{Infobox Artwork|image_file=Jacob_van_Oost_(I)_-_Two_boys_blowing_bubbles.jpg |alt=|image_size=300px|title=Two Boys Blowing Bubbles|other_language_1=|other_title_1=|artist=[[Michaelina Wautier]]|year=1640s|medium=[[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[canvas]]|height_metric=90.5|width_metric=121.3|height_imperial=|width_imperial=|metric_unit=cm|imperial_unit=in}}



'''Two Boys Blowing Bubbles''' is a painting by the Flemish artist [[Michaelina Wautier]]. It was painted in the 1640s. Besides the two boys, the painting depicts a candle and a sandtimer, both symbols of the passing of time.  <ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mas.be/sites/mas/files/MAS_Michaelina_gids_EN.pdf|title=Michaelina, Baroque’s Leading Lady|last=|first=|date=|website=|page=20/21|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref>

The painting was previously attributed to [[Jacob van Oost]]. However, research done in 2007 led to the re-attribution to Wautier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://samblog.seattleartmuseum.org/2018/08/boys-blowing-bubbles/|title=Object of the Week: Boys Blowing Bubbles {{!}} SAM Blog|website=samblog.seattleartmuseum.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref>

The painting hangs in the [[Seattle Art Museum]] who purchased it in 1958.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://art.seattleartmuseum.org/objects/13629/boys-blowing-bubbles?ctx=e40c99e0-3812-46bc-a319-5044f57701f1&idx=0|title=Boys Blowing Bubbles – Works – eMuseum|website=art.seattleartmuseum.org|language=en|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref> A second version by Wautier is in a private collection in Spain.<ref name=":0" />

